    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1" facs="../images/25775_1.png"/>
            <div type="correspondence-action">
                <ab style="writing-mode: vertical-lr" rendition="#center">
                    <name type="person" ref="psn:peter_still">Peter Freedman</name>
                </ab>
                <ab rendition="#center">
                    <handShift medium="pencil"/><name>James O. Cousins</name> <placeName><hi rendition="#u">Cincinnati Ohio</hi></placeName><lb/>
                    Mailed by <name type="person">A. J. Gorden</name> of <placeName>Philadelphia<lb/>
                    <hi rendition="#u">Pa</hi></placeName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <pb n="2" facs="../images/25775_2.png"/>
            <div>
              <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#indent3">
                    <handShift medium="black-ink"/>
                    <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                    <date when="1850-08-07">August 7th, 1850</date>
                </dateline>
              </opener>
            </div>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Last Friday afternoon, <name type="person" ref="psn:peter_still">Peter Freedman</name><lb/>
                    was brought to this office by a man<lb/>
                    whom I was <choice><sic>partialy</sic><corr>partially</corr></choice> acquainted with,<lb/>
                    <add place="above">the</add> object of Peter was to see if he could<lb/>
                    gain some instruction how he might<lb/>
                    find his parents &amp; relatives, <choice><sic>whome</sic><corr>whom</corr></choice><lb/>
                    he had been sold away from for<lb/>
                    43 years. The remarks made by the<lb/> 
                    stranger much surprised me and I<lb/>
                    soon began to make <choice><sic>inquirery</sic><corr>inquiry</corr></choice><lb/>
                    as to his parents and their names,<lb/>
                    He <del rend="strikethrough">an</del> immediately gave the names<lb/>
                    of his father, mother, and the brother<lb/>
                    who was also sold with him at<lb/>
                    the same time. By this time I<lb/>
                    perceived that a wonderful development<lb/> was about to be made.<lb/>
                    My feelings became <del rend="strikethrough">unt</del> unutterable,<lb/> although I endeavored to <choice><sic>surpress</sic><corr>suppress</corr></choice><lb/>
                    them with much effort, but the<lb/>
                    fact that this Peter was one of<lb/>
                    my long absent brothers stared me<lb/>
                    too full in the face to gainsay<lb/>
                    or dispute the evidence for one<lb/>
                    moment. Thus a brother whom<lb/>
                    <pb n="3" facs="../images/25775_3.png"/>
                    whom I had never before seen<lb/>
                    was introduced to me in this most<lb/>
                    wonderful manner. It would<lb/>
                    afford me much pleasure to<lb/>
                    make fuller statement concerning<lb/>
                    this matter but for want of time<lb/>
                    I must <choice><sic>forbare</sic><corr>forbear</corr></choice> at present<lb/>
                    Suffice it to say that Peter<lb/>
                    found his mother, 5 brothers &amp;<lb/>
                    3 sisters situated <choice><sic>comfort<add place="above">a</add>ly</sic><corr>comfortably</corr></choice> in life<lb/>
                </p>
                
                <closer>
                    <salute>From Peter S <choice><sic>younges</sic><corr>youngest</corr></choice> brother,</salute>
                    <signed><name ref="psn:william_still">Wm Still.</name></signed>
                    <placeName>no 31 North fifth St.</placeName>
                    <placeName>Philadelphia Pa</placeName>
                </closer>
            </div>
